Your point was that the officers should be able to neutralise a percieved threat instantly yes? I'm not sure i'd be totally comfortable with the implications of that if i was you. It is of course easy for me to say - i'm not a police officer - but something i think perhaps you're missing is that in the majority of cases a British bobby with a nightstick is gonna be facing a criminal opponent with similar (lower threat) weapons. <br>
<br>
The fact that any drunken loon or assorted nut job could be packing a firearm in the US has to mean harsher procedures are required. <br>
<br>
This last is gonna sound very cold blooded but if a policeman doesn't have a firearm, he'll probably have to attempt to find a less confrontational method of dealing with a situation than sticking a gun in the suspects face, wouldn't you agree? The very act of threatening with a firearm surely increases the chance of panic or irrational behaviour in a suspect doesn't it?<br>
<br>
This possibly puts the officer at increased risk but i wonder if this point doesn't factor into the doctrine....<br>
<br>
I should probably end this post by saying (no matter how i may sound) that I have the greatest respect for anybody who places themselves at risk for the good of their fellow man. Police officers in particular (possibly the most thankless job under the sun).<br>
