<br>
Texas still has laws on the books dating back to the 1800's "Tombstone" Style of law.  Meaning that gunfights in the street can be validated and written off by 3 witnesses not related or known to you.  The carry/concealed laws in Texas are also some of the most lax, allowing you to carry a gun in plain sight at nearly all times.  However this is still restricted from Government buildings and any store or speakeasy that serves alcohol of any sort.<br>
<br>
First time in Texas I watched two Rangers chase a man across 6 lanes of Interstate traffic and beat him senseless as he tried to climb a security fence along the other side. =P <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#575757><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/udwelfnvhal.showPublicProfile?language=EN>DwelfnVhal</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 245<br> <font color=#E9D756>(6/16/02 2:00:10 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/femarrdragonsandplanes.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3405.topic&index=37>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Wow, Crime, that's tough.</span><hr size=1> Glori, As I said in my post above I don't neccessarily disagree that the officer was justified in this particular case.<br>
<br>
Neither would I ever suggest that an American police officer should go unarmed  - the relative laxness of gun control in the US could turn any high stress situation into a potentially lethal circumstance for the officer. <br>
<br>
Police in this country are armed when they attempt to take down a drug dealer or whatever, but, thanks to stricter gun control (too strict actually imho) over here the level of threat for general policing is 'somewhat' reduced. When a bobby pulls over someone for a traffic violation the likelyhood of his getting shot is miniscule... <br>
<br>
If we take the random traffic stop as an example, suppose the US driver is a felon who thinks he may be going to jail and want's to avoid that at all costs, he's got a gun, he wants to resist arrest and he knows when he does so the cop has the ability to shoot him, in a situation of such stress you think the guy is gonna take the sensible route?<br>
<br>
A better example (A RL one shown on one of those horrible 'reality TV' shows we get piped over here) is this. The camera shows an officer making a routine traffic stop, as he's getting the occupants out of the car the passenger (who has a warrent out on him) tries to grab the officers gun from it's holster, he fails and then attempts to flee after a scuffle. The officer, reacting to having had his life threatened, gun in hand having fought for possession of it, reacts by firing off 5 shots at the fleeing man , starting at a maximum of about 2 yards seperation (!)<br>
<br>
As the announcer proclaims &quot;Amazingly, the suspect gets away with only a bullet hole in his jacket&quot; <br>
<br>
How many occassions does something like this occur and the criminal (who is still at the end of the day a human being) doesn't get so lucky? Remember that we cannot assume the felon intended to turn the weapon on the officer if he had gained the weapon (although the risk is quite high, especially if the officer attempts to regain possession). Note that if the officers gun hadn't been present the situation quite possibly wouldn't have escalated in the fashion it did. The officer, with his unarmed combat training, pepper spray and authority etc would still have had the ability to control the situation.  <br>
<br>
Firearms increase the lethality of any situation just by being present.<br>
<br>
Having said that, I think (I no longer read the papers or watch the news - too depressing) there is an upsurge in guncrimes and general visciousness here as well so how long the British police can remain unarmed I don't know...<br>
<br>
